uhoun  .","History: This prominent early American name was brought across the Atlantic Ocean by Scotch-Irish pioneers who entered Pennsylvania <i>c.</i> 1733. The American statesman John <i>c.</i> Calhoun (1782–1850), born in Abbeville District, SC, served in both houses of Congress, was secretary of war, and vice president of the US (1825–32)."]},{"name":"Kahoun","meanings":["Irish: variant of Scottish   Colquhoun  ."]},{"name":"Cahoon","meanings":["Irish (Down and Antrim): variant (reflecting the traditional pronunciation) of Scottish   Colquhoun  ."]},{"name":"Calhoon","meanings":["Irish: variant of Scottish   Colquhoun  ."]}]},{"name":"Mary","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Latin <i>Maria</i> via Old Welsh <i>Meir</i>.  See  <b>Mary</b> ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Mary Colquhoun was born in 1397, in Houston, Renfrewshire, Scotland, United Kingdom, her father, Humphrey Colquhoun 6th Colquhoun of that Ilk, was 47 and her mother, Margaret Fraser, was 37. She married John Padraig Houston in Lochawe, Argyll, Scotland, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in 1456, in Houston, Renfrewshire, Scotland, at the age of 59."},"et":{"1397–1456":"1397–1456","1404–1450":"1404–1450","1355–1425":"1355–1425","1400–1450":"1400–1450","1350–1406":"1350–1406","1360–Female":"1360–Surnud","1404":"1404","1425":"1425","5 April 1406":"5. aprill 1406","1456":"1456","1400":"1400","1355":"1355","1397":"1397","1450":"1450","Abt 1379":"umbes 1379","1350":"1350","1360":"1360","1406":"1406","Lochawe Argyll  Scotland":"Lochawe, Argyll, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","West Dunbartonshire, Scotland":"Dunbartonshire, Scotland","Paisley, Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Paisley, Renfrewshire, Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Scotland":"Šotimaa, United Kingdom","Houston, Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Houston, Renfrewshire, Scotland"},"fi":{"1397–1456":"1397–1456","1404–1450":"1404–1450","1355–14